'''Morris Mike Medavoy''' (born January 21, 1941) is an [[United States|American]] film producer and executive, co-founder of [[Orion Pictures]] (1978), former chairman of [[TriStar Pictures]], former head of production for [[United Artists]] (1974<U+2013>1978) and current chairman and [[CEO]] of [[Phoenix Pictures]].

==Biography==
===Early life and career===
Medavoy was born in 1941, in Shanghai, China. His father, Michael, was a garage mechanic, and his mother, Dora, had a dress shop for Chinese actresses.<ref name=therrapw>{{cite web|last=Medavoy |first=Mike |url=http://www.thewrap.com/deal-central/blog-post/mike-medavoy-china-blog-19609?page=0,0 |title=Mike Medavoy: Revisiting My Roots as a Jewish Child in Shanghai &#124; The Wrap Deal Central |publisher=Thewrap.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref><ref>[http://books.google.ca/books?id=OqUwAQAAIAAJ&q=Mike+Medavoy+shanghai+father&dq=Mike+Medavoy+shanghai+father&source=bl&ots=jrnoIWL1Mu&sig=0L8dezqYJOz_Kb1EwuaaUGqiaiM&hl=en&redir_esc=y]</ref><ref>http://articles.latimes.com/1995-12-13/news/ls-13359_1_mike-medavoy</ref> His parents were both from Jewish families, with his mother having been born in [[Harbin]], [[Manchuria]] (to parents from [[Odessa]]) and his father in the [[Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Bloom |first=Nate |url=http://www.interfaithfamily.com/arts_and_entertainment/popular_culture/Interfaith_Celebrities_The_2011_Oscars.shtml |title=Interfaith Celebrities: The 2011 Oscars |publisher=InterfaithFamily.com |date=2011-02-15 |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref><ref name=therrapw/> Medavoy lived in [[Chile]] from 1947 to 1957, and he study at historic [[Liceo Valent<U+00ED>n Letelier de Santiago]], <ref>{{cite web|last=Medavoy |first=Mike |url=http://www.thewrap.com/deal-central/blog-post/mike-medavoy-china-blog-19609?page=0,1 |title=Mike Medavoy: Revisiting My Roots as a Jewish Child in Shanghai &#124; The Wrap Deal Central |publisher=Thewrap.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref> where he learned to speak Spanish fluently.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} He became an American citizen in 1963,<ref>Medavoy, Mike and Young, Josh (2002). ''You're Only as Good as Your Next One: 100 Great Films, 100 Good Films, and 100 for Which I Should Be Shot'' (p. 215). [[New York City]]: [[Atria Books]]</ref> and graduated from UCLA that same year.

Medavoy began his career at [[Universal Studios]] in 1964. In 1965 he became an agent at the [[General Artists Corporation]] and later moving into the vice president position of the [[Creative Management Agency]].

===The [[New Hollywood]]===
Later he joined [[Creative Management]] as its vice president of the motion picture department in 1967. There, he worked with [[Steven Spielberg]] and [[Francis Ford Coppola]] amongst others and headed to IFA in 1970.<ref name=Phoenix>("Mike Medavoy." Phoenixpictures.com, 9 September 2009. Web. 9 September 2009. <http://www.phoenixpictures.com/about-us/mike-medavoy.html.)</ref>

In 1974, United Artists brought Medavoy in as senior vice president of production. There, he was part of the team responsible for ''[[One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest (film)|One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest]]'', ''[[Rocky]]'', and ''[[Annie Hall]]'', which won best Pictures Oscars<U+00AE> in 1975, 1976 and 1977 respectively. United Artists made a number of other notable films at the time, including ''[[Apocalypse Now]]'', ''[[Raging Bull]]'', ''[[Network (film)|Network]]'' and ''[[Coming Home (1978 film)|Coming Home]]''.<ref name=Phoenix/>

===Orion Pictures===
In 1978, Medavoy co-founded [[Orion Pictures]]. During his tenure there, Orion released films such notable and successful films as ''[[Platoon (film)|Platoon]]'', ''[[Amadeus (film)|Amadeus]]'', ''[[Robocop]]'', ''[[Hannah and Her Sisters]]'', ''[[The Terminator]]'', ''[[Dances with Wolves]]'', and ''[[The Silence of the Lambs (film)|The Silence of the Lambs]]''.<ref name=Phoenix/>

===TriStar Pictures===
In 1990, Medavoy became the chairman of [[TriStar Pictures]] where he oversaw release of films such as ''[[Philadelphia (film)|Philadelphia]]'', ''[[Terminator 2: Judgment Day]]'', ''[[Sleepless in Seattle]]'', ''[[Cliffhanger (film)|Cliffhanger]]'', ''[[The Fisher King (film)|The Fisher King]]'', ''[[Legends of the Fall]]'' and ''[[Hook (film)|Hook]].<ref name=Phoenix/>

===Phoenix Pictures===
[[File:Mike Medavoy by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|upright|Medavoy at the 2007 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]]]In 1995, Medavoy co-founded [[Phoenix Pictures]]. As its chairman and CEO, Mike helped produce films such as ''[[The People vs. Larry Flint]]'', ''[[The Mirror Has Two Faces]]'', ''[[U Turn (1997 film)|U Turn]]'', ''[[Apt Pupil (film)|Apt Pupil]]'', ''[[The Thin Red Line (1998 film)|The Thin Red Line]]'', ''[[The 6th Day]]'', ''[[Basic (film)|Basic]]'', ''[[All the King's Men (2006 film)|All the King's Men]]'', ''[[Zodiac (film)|Zodiac]]'', ''[[Pathfinder (2007 film)|Pathfinder]]'' and ''[[Miss Potter]]'', among others. ''The Thin Red Line'' and ''The People vs. Larry Flint'' each received Oscar nominations.<ref name=Phoenix/>

Most recently, Phoenix Pictures has produced ''[[Shutter Island (film)|Shutter Island]]'' and ''[[Black Swan (film)|Black Swan]]''. ''Shutter Island'' was released on February 19, 2010, earning over $42 million its opening weekend. ''Black Swan'' was directed by [[Darren Aronofsky]] and won numerous awards including the Oscar<U+00AE> and Golden Globe for Best Actress ([[Natalie Portman]]).<ref name=Phoenix/>

In 2011, Medavoy announced his newest project surrounding the [[2010 Copiap<U+00F3> mining accident|2010 Chilean mining accident]] that left 33 men trapped underground for 69 days. Medavoy will collaborate with Chilean officials and Academy Award-nominated screenwriter [[Jos<U+00E9> Rivera (playwright)|Jos<U+00E9> Rivera]] to create an authentic retelling of this story that, as Medavoy explains, <U+201C>at its heart, [is] about the triumph of the human spirit and a testament to the courage and perseverance of the Chilean people<U+201D>.<ref name=Phoenix/>

Also in 2011, Medavoy announced his collaboration with The Shanghai Film Group to create both a feature film and six-hour miniseries. The feature, an adaptation of the novel ''The Cursed Piano'', is a love story set in Japanese-occupied China concerning prosecuted Jews seeking refuge from an occupied Europe. The mini-series, ''Tears of a Sparrow'', will focus in greater detail on the experience of these Jews in Shanghai.

Mike is also working on an adaptation of DANDELION WINE, adapted from the novel by the late Ray Bradbury. <ref name=Phoenix/>

